","1385":"1385","1066":"1066","1042":"1042","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","Cottingham, East Riding Yorkshire, England":"England","Valmont, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France":"Valmont, Seine-Maritime, Normandie, Frankrijk","Stuteville, Lower, Haute-Normandie, France":"Haute-Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1042–1107":"1042–1107","1107":"1107","1100":"1100","1385":"1385","1066":"1066","1042":"1042","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","Cottingham, East Riding Yorkshire, England":"England","Valmont, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France":"Valmont, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France","Stuteville, Lower, Haute-Normandie, France":"Upper Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Stuteville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Estouteville or Etoutteville in Seine-Maritime."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":24,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705183,"age":44,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705184,"age":54,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Robert De Stuteville I was born in 1042, in Upper Normandy, France. He died in 1107, in England, at the age of 65, and was buried in Valmont, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France."},"et":{"1042–1107":"1042–1107","1107":"1107","1100":"1100","1385":"1385","1066":"1066","1042":"1042","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","Cottingham, East Riding Yorkshire, England":"England","Valmont, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France":"Valmont, Seine-Maritime, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Stuteville, Lower, Haute-Normandie, France":"Haute-Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1042–1107":"1042–1107","1107":"1107","1100":"1100","1385":"1385","1066":"1066","1042":"1042","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","Cottingham, East Riding Yorkshire, England":"England","Valmont, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France":"Valmont, Seine-Maritime, Normandie, Ranska","Stuteville, Lower, Haute-Normandie, France":"Haute-Normandie, Ranska"},"fr":{"1042–1107":"1042–1107","1107":"1107","1100":"1100","1385":"1385","1066":"1066","1042":"1042","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","Cottingham, East Riding Yorkshire, England":"Angleterre","Valmont, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France":"Valmont, Seine-Maritime, Normandie, France","Stuteville, Lower, Haute-Normandie, France":"Haute-Normandie, France","historicEvents":[{"id":2528823,"age":58,"year":"1100","toYear":"1385","julianDay":2122827,"description":"Le nom de la localité est attesté sous les formes Walemunt (sans date) ou au XIIe siècle, Galemunt au XIIe siècle, Walemont en 1236, Walemont en 1262, Walemont en 1272, Vallemont en 1300, Valmont en 1385. Il s'agit d'une formation toponymique médiévale en -mont au sens de « colline, hauteur », appellatif précédé du nom de personne scandinave Váli (vieux danois Wale) que l'on rencontre dans plusieurs noms de lieux de Normandie","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Robert De Stuteville I est né en 1042, à Haute-Normandie, France. Il est décédé en 1107, à Angleterre, à l’âge de 65 ans, et a été enterré à Valmont, Seine-Maritime, Norma